Project: Machine Learning: Personal Loan Campaign

Business Context

Project: Machine Learning: Personal Loan Campaign Context: AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data Scientist at AllLife Bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objectives

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and to identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary

Dataset Features Description

ID: Unique Customer Identifier
Age: Customer's age in completed years
Experience: Years of professional experience
Income: Annual income (in thousand dollars)
ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code
Family: Family size of the customer
CCAvg: Average monthly credit card spending (in thousand dollars)
Education: Education Level (1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional)
Mortgage: Value of house mortgage, if any (in thousand dollars)
Personal_Loan: Whether customer accepted personal loan in last campaign
Securities_Account: Whether customer has securities account with the bank
CD_Account: Whether customer has certificate of deposit account
Online: Whether customer uses internet banking facilities
CreditCard: Whether customer uses credit card from other banks (excluding All Life Bank)

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plotloc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

  • Mortgage Data: 69% of customers have no mortgage; remaining hold 99K-635K (In Dollor) mortgages

Categorical Variable Composition

Family Structure

  • 29.4% Single individuals
  • 25.9% Two-member families
  • 24.4% Four-member families
  • 20.2% Three-member families

Educational Background

  • 41.9% Undergraduate degree holders
  • 30.0% Advanced/Professional degrees
  • 28.1% Graduate degree holders

Geographic Distribution

  • Top Cities: Los Angeles, San Diego, San Francisco, Berkeley, Sacramento
  • Dominant State: California leads customer residency

Financial Service Adoption

  • CD Accounts: 94% without certificates of deposit, 6% with CD accounts
  • Online Banking: 59.7% active users, 40.3% non-users
  • External Credit Cards: 70.6% without external cards, 29.4% with external cards
  • Loan Acceptance: 90.4% declined offers, 9.6% accepted personal loans

Multivariate Analysis Insights

Correlation Matrix Findings

  • Strong Correlation: Age and Experience show near-perfect correlation (0.98)
  • Moderate Correlation: Income and credit card spending correlate at 0.65
  • Minimal Correlation: All other variable pairs show insignificant relationships

Target Variable Drivers

Significant Positive Influences

  • Income Levels: Higher earnings increase loan acceptance probability
  • Family Size: Larger households show greater loan uptake

Neutral Factors (Minimal Impact)

import pgeocode

nomi = pgeocode.Nominatim('us')
def get_city_state(zipcode):
    result = nomi.query_postal_code(zipcode)
    if pd.isna(result['postal_code']):
        return pd.Series({'City': None, 'State': None})
    return pd.Series({
        'City': result['place_name'],
        'State': result['state_code']
    })


data[['City', 'State']] = data['ZIPCode'].apply(get_city_state)

Model Evaluation

We define a utility function to collate all the metrics into a single data frame, and another to plot the confusion matrix.

In[206]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In[207]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    # Predict the target values using the provided model and predictors
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Compute the confusion matrix comparing the true target values with the predicted values
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    # Create labels for each cell in the confusion matrix with both count and percentage
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)    # reshaping to a matrix

    # Set the figure size for the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Plot the confusion matrix as a heatmap with the labels
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")

    # Add a label to the y-axis
    plt.ylabel("True label")

    # Add a label to the x-axis
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
Note: We want to maximize the F1 Score to ensure that we reduce both the chances of approving non-credible applications as well as rejecting credible ones.

Decision Tree (Pre-pruning)

In[216]:
# define the parameters of the tree to iterate over
max_depth_values = np.arange(2, 11, 2)
max_leaf_nodes_values = np.arange(10, 51, 10)
min_samples_split_values = np.arange(10, 51, 10)

# initialize variables to store the best model and its performance
best_estimator = None
best_score_diff = float('inf')

# iterate over all combinations of the specified parameter values
for max_depth in max_depth_values:
    for max_leaf_nodes in max_leaf_nodes_values:
        for min_samples_split in min_samples_split_values:

            # initialize the tree with the current set of parameters
            estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(
                max_depth=max_depth,
                max_leaf_nodes=max_leaf_nodes,
                min_samples_split=min_samples_split,
                random_state=42
            )

            # fit the model to the training data
            estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

            # make predictions on the training and test sets
            y_train_pred = estimator.predict(X_train)
            y_test_pred = estimator.predict(X_test)

            # calculate F1 scores for training and test sets
            train_f1_score = f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
            test_f1_score = f1_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

            # calculate the absolute difference between training and test F1 scores
            score_diff = abs(train_f1_score - test_f1_score)

            # update the best estimator and best score if the current one has a smaller score difference
            if score_diff < best_score_diff:
                best_score_diff = score_diff
                best_estimator = estimator

clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

# Compute the cost complexity pruning path for the model using the training data
path_1 = clf.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)

# Extract the array of effective alphas from the pruning path
ccp_alphas = abs(path_1.ccp_alphas)

# Extract the array of total impurities at each alpha along the pruning path
impurities = path_1.impurities

clfs = []

    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha, random_state=42)

    # Fit the classifier to the training data
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Append the trained classifier to the list
    clfs.append(clf)

# Print the number of nodes in the last tree along with its ccp_alpha value

Project Synthesis and Strategic Guidance

Overview

This analytics initiative successfully constructed predictive frameworks to pinpoint prospective personal loan clients for All Life Bank. By systematically examining customer demographic patterns, financial activities, and institutional relationships, the Post Pruning method proved most effective, delivering 99% predictive accuracy alongside outstanding precision (96%) and recall rates (93%).

Performance Analysis and Critical Insights

Model Evaluation Outcomes:

  • Post-Pruning: Exceptional results featuring 99% accuracy, 96% precision, 93% recall, and 0.95 F1-measure
  • Pre-Pruning): Reduced effectiveness relative to optimized version with 99% accuracy, 95% precision, 91% recall, and 0.93 F1-measure
  • sklearn default: Exhibited overfitting challenges, confirming pruning necessity

Determinant Success Variables:

  1. Earnings Benchmark: $100K yearly income serving as principal decision parameter
  2. Academic Achievement: Advanced/Professional educational background substantially elevates loan approval likelihood
  3. Digital Interaction: Online banking participants demonstrate enhanced conversion probabilities
  4. Financial Instruments: Certificate of deposit owners and investment account clients represent optimal prospects

Strategic Implementation Framework

Priority Marketing Initiatives

Primary Audience Clusters:

  1. "Elite Career Professionals"

    • Annual earnings exceeding $100K with graduate-level education
    • Projected conversion probability: 90%+
    • Strategic approach: Customized premium financial solutions

  2. "Expanding Households"

    • Family units 1 member, 35-40 age bracket, property loan obligations
    • Conversion catalysts: Lifecycle requirements and financial responsibilities
    • Strategic approach: Tailored family-oriented lending options

  3. "Wealth-Protected Clients"

    • Fixed deposit account owners with investment portfolios
    • Diminished risk characteristics with collateral capabilities
    • Strategic approach: Secured lending instruments

Marketing Efficiency Enhancement

Resource Distribution:

  • Amplified Attention: Clients with $100K+ earnings, advanced degrees, fixed deposit accounts
  • Diminished Emphasis: Pre-retirement customers, digital-only banking users, limited-income groups
  • Experimental Focus: High-earning clients with property loans and substantial credit card expenditure

Service Delivery Advancements

Digital Interface Upgrades:

  • Streamline online loan request user interface
  • Deploy customized notifications for pre-qualified segments
  • Create mobile-optimized application workflows for technologically adept clients

Risk Assessment Protocols:

  • Establish graduated interest structures aligned with identified risk categories
  • Design specialized oversight for clients with elevated credit card usage despite conversion potential
  • Develop proactive monitoring mechanisms utilizing decision tree parameters

Operational Execution Guidelines

Sales Force Direction:

Immediate Engagement:

  • Clients satisfying income and education criteria
  • Fixed deposit account holders with domestic responsibilities
  • Mortgage clients exhibiting consistent repayment history

Cautious Approach:

  • Elevated credit card utilization clients (default risk monitoring)
  • Customers with minimal banking service utilization

Lower Priority:

  • Approaching retirement clients (limited conversion potential)
  • Exclusive digital banking users hesitant toward additional services

Technical Deployment Timeline

Initial Phase (30-day execution):

  1. Incorporate optimized decision tree algorithm into customer management platform
  2. Educate sales personnel on identified client categories
  3. Launch digital engagement strategies for online banking users

Intermediate Phase (60-day implementation):

  1. Construct automated evaluation system for new client acquisitions
  2. Develop performance monitoring interface for marketing initiatives
  3. Initiate comparative testing for diverse promotional approaches

Extended Phase (90+ day progression):

  1. Ongoing model refinement incorporating fresh client information
  2. Broaden application to forecast additional banking service adoption
  3. Integrate with instantaneous customer engagement platforms

Risk Assessment and Countermeasures

Technical Vulnerabilities:

  • Income parameter dependency: Track economic fluctuations influencing client earnings
  • Temporal data variance: Conduct quarterly model verification
  • Inaccurate predictions: Preserve expert evaluation for significant decisions

Commercial Vulnerabilities:

  • Segment overconcentration: Prevent excessive focus on individual customer groups
  • Market competition: Anticipate rival responses to effective targeting
  • Legal adherence: Verify targeting methodologies comply with equitable lending regulations

Concluding Assessment

The refined decision tree methodology equips All Life Bank with a sophisticated, practical instrument for personal loan client identification. Through concentration on established high-probability segments and execution of recommended strategic measures, the institution can anticipate:

  • Enhanced conversion rates through 90%+ accurate client targeting
  • Optimized marketing expenditure via concentrated resource distribution
  • Superior client satisfaction through individualized, appropriate proposals
  • Advanced risk assessment utilizing evidence-based decision frameworks
